Exercise 1 [20 points]

As output of this exercise, you are required to submit an R script (A1_ex1.R) able to complete the operations listed below. The data represents the monthy electricity demand for Victoria, Australia. The variables available for this analysis are:

Variable Description
year Year of the record
month Month of the record
demand Total electricity demand (MWh)
temp Monthly average temperature in Melbourne in degree celsius (BOM site 086071)
  1. [2 marks] Read the csv file vic_elect.csv into a tibble named X.
  2. [2 marks] Display the structure of X using str(X).
  3. [4 marks] Calculate and display the total sum of all demand in the dataset.
  4. [4 marks] Calculate and display the average demand for all records where month is Jul.
  5. [4 marks] Compute and show the median of demand of all records where temp is below 15.
  6. [4 marks] Find the record with the highest demand, and display its corresponding year and month.

Exercise 2 [20 points]

As output of this exercise, you are required to submit an R script (A1_ex2.R) able to complete the operations listed below.

Use set.seed()

Please note: as there is random number generation involved, it is of paramount importance that we are able to generate the same random numbers. In order to achieve this, at the beginning of the script, you need to run a command to set the random seed.

  1. [1 marks] Set the random seed: set.seed(2025)
  2. [4 marks] By using a for loop, create a list X with N = 100 slots. In each slot, store a list containing two elements:
    • name, a character string in the format n_i, where i represents the slot number.
    • vect, a numeric vector of 5 elements sampled from a normal distribution with \(\mu=20\) and \(\sigma = 10.\)
  3. [2 marks] Display the structure of X using (str(X)).
  4. [4 marks] Compute the sum of the values of vect in each slot and show the output by using a for loop. The output must be a vector of 100 values.
  5. [4 marks] Create a matrix M (not a data frame) of size \(100\times\) 5 using the 100 vect objects stored in X by using a for loop.
  6. [5 marks] Using a while loop, calculate and accumulate the column totals of M one by one until the running sum exceeds 4000, then display the individual column totals, the final running sum, and the number of columns needed to reach this threshold.

Exercise 3 [50 points]

In this exercise you are required to read the files A1_Ex3_signif.csv and A1_Ex3_not_signif.csv and write the code to test the hypothesis

\(H_0: \beta=0\) against \(H_1: \beta \ne 0\),

where \(\beta\) is the slope parameter of a simple linear model

\(Y_i = \alpha + \beta X_i + \epsilon_i\),

with \(\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma)\) and \(i \in 1,\dots, N\). \(N\) is the sample size.

The structure of the test is:

  1. State the Null Hypothesis and the Alternative Hypothesis
  2. Check the assumptions by plotting
    1. \(y\) vs \(x\),
    2. the regression residuals \(e_i\) vs the fitted values \(\hat y\) and
    3. the histogram of the regression residuals \(e_i\). Only 3 graphs are required for this point, there is no need to comment.
  3. Perform the linear regression and report the followings:
    • values of the estimated slope \(\hat \beta\),
    • the \(95\%\) CIs for \(\beta\),
    • the value of the test statistics \(t\),
    • the degree of freedom \(df\), and
    • the p-value.
  4. State the decision of the hypothesis test at the 5% significance level, i.e.Â whether to reject or not to reject the Null Hypothesis.
  5. Write a conclusion to the test, i.e., one or two sentences in English in which you explain the results and describe the presence or absence of a relationship between \(X\) and \(Y\).

The linear regression model must be run with the R command lm(). Some information needed to complete the exercise can be directly extracted from the regression output object (explorable with str() or the broom package), while other parts may require some manual calculation.

Produce a single file named A1_ex3.R containing the code that generates all required results.

You can solve this exercise at different levels.

  • Pass Level [0-20 points]: writing a sequence of commands that work only on the given data sets. In this case, you need to run the test twice, once per data set, and each time you need to write the conclusion that is correct for the specific case you are considering.
  • Credit level [20-28 points]: As at the pass level, but writing the conclusions programmatically, i.e., using a function that takes in input the values of \(\hat \beta\) and the p-value and is able to output the correct message.
  • Distinction level [28-36 points]: Building on your work at Credit level, fully solving the problem with the following functions, called sequentially from a script:
    • hypothesis(file_name)
    • assumptions(file_name) (Please note, you will need to run the linear regression model to get the residuals)
    • fit1 <- fit(file_name)
    • decision(fit1)
    • conclusion(fit1)
  • High Distinction [36-40 points]: As at the distinction level, but the function fit1 <- fit(file_name) returns an object of class mylm. Methods named decision.mylm() and conclusion.mylm() can be called with decision(fit1) and conclusion(fit1). The full test can be called with a function mytest(file_name), which calls everything needed and outputs a nicely formatted report (i.e.Â a sequence of cat and plot (or ggplot) commands from all the functions called sequentially).

Tip: Please include a comment at the top of your script indicating which level of the question you are attempting. For example, you could write: I am aiming for a Credit level for this part.
